The two white men are accused of forcing a black man into a coffin and threatening to set it on fire. JOHANNESBURG Two men accused of attacking a man in an apparent racially-motivated incident have abandoned their bail application. The pair appeared in the Middelburg Magistrates Court in Mpumalanga on Wednesday morning. They are accused of forcing the black man into a coffin and threatening to set it on fire. The incident occurred earlier this month and a video of the attack circulated on social media. CIC @Julius_S_Malema asked where are statements from Pastors &amp; Bishops condemning what white farmers did to this black man pic.twitter.com/pBBoJwoMN7The accused persons, Willem Oosthuizen and Theo Martins Jackson have been charged with kidnapping and assault with intent to do grievous bodily harm.In a video circulating on social media, one of the men, an Afrikaaner, is seen forcing Victor Rethabile Mlotshwa into a coffin while his accomplice threatens to set it alight.The Economic Freedom Fighters have released a statement confirming the incident, which is said to have occurred at JM De Beer Boerdery next to Komati Power Station.(Edited by Leeto M Khoza)